SIMPLE: saline
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Saline
<hw>Sa"line</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>salin</ets>, fr. L. <ets>sal</ets> salt: cf. L. <ets>salinae</ets>
salt works, <ets>salinum</ets> saltcellar. See <er>Salt</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting of salt, or containing salt; <as>as,
<ex>saline</ex> particles; <ex>saline</ex> substances; a <ex>saline</ex>
cathartic</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of the quality of salt; salty; <as>as, a
<ex>saline</ex> taste</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saline</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Saline
<hw>Sa"line</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>saline</ets>. See <er>Saline</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>A salt
spring; a place where salt water is collected in the earth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saline</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Saline
<hw>Sal"ine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A crude potash obtained from beet-root residues
and other similar sources.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>salin</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med. Chem.)</fld> <def>A metallic salt; esp., a
salt of potassium, sodium, lithium, or magnesium, used in
medicine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 3. (Med., Biochemistry) A saline solution, esp. normal saline, or
isotonic saline, used for infusion, to maintain blood pressure. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Salineness</ent>⟦br⟧
